"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s28_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"dfc1ff",
"children":[
"Angioedema is characterized by a sudden, temporary edema, usually of the lips, face, hands, feet, penis, or scrotum. Abdominal pain may be present owing to bowel wall edema."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"4cf1fd",
"children":[
"Mast cell–mediated angioedema is often associated with urticaria, bronchospasm, or hypotension. This can be the result of an allergic reaction (peanuts, shrimp, latex, insect stings) or to direct mast cell stimulation (",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs",
"children":[
"NSAIDs"
]
},
","
]
},
" radiocontrast media, opioids)."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"1d57a9",
"children":[
"Bradykinin-mediated angioedema is NOT associated with urticaria. In the setting of angioedema without urticaria, the differential is very limited. Diagnose by testing for quantitative and functional levels of C1 esterase inhibitor and C4 complement levels."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_pm_s28_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"6521d9",
"children":[
"In patients with urticaria and angioedema, do not diagnose hereditary angioedema."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s28_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"86a744",
"children":[
"Select epinephrine for acute episodes of mast cell–mediated (allergic) angioedema with airway compromise or hypotension."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"2",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_pm_f09"
],
"forceOpen":true
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s28_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"5c538d",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 40-year-old man has a 1-year history of cramping abdominal pain and 2- to 3-day episodes of face and hand swelling that have not responded completely to epinephrine and antihistamines. His mother died suddenly of “suffocation.”"
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"38e842",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose hereditary angioedema. For management, select serum C4 and C1 inhibitor levels (functional and antigenic) and treatment of severe acute episodes of swelling with C1 inhibitor concentrate."
]
}
]
}
]
},
